[152.388895, "o", "AUDIT FINDINGS: FRAUD MODEL EVALUATION DRAFT REPORT\r\n==================================================\r\nAudited by: Senior AI Consultant / Lead Fraud Analyst\r\nDate: May 27, 2026\r\nSubject: Technical and Operational Audit of Draft Evaluation Report by Alex Chen (Junior Analyst)\r\n\r\nThis document contains detailed findings from our technical audit of the draft fraud model evaluation report. The audit revealed multiple critical errors, misleading claims, and major analytical gaps. Deploying the model under the draft's assumptions would have overwhelmed Fraud Operations and led to sub-optimal financial results.\r\n\r\nBelow are the 6 primary findings, including explanations of what is wrong, why it matters, and the corrected interpretations.\r\n\r\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\nFINDING 1: Data Pipeline Failure (Out-of-Period Data and Duplicate Leakage)\r\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n* Claim in Draft:\r\n  \"The XGBoost fraud detection model was evaluated against 5,650 held-out transactions.\"\r\n* What is Wrong:\r\n  The evaluation dataset export was not pre-processed or filtered. It contains 585 records from May (May 1 to May 11, 2026) which fall outside the designated scoring period of January 15 - April 30, 2026 specified in dataset_info.txt.\r\n  Crucially, 500 of these 585 records are exact duplicates (by TransactionID) of transactions already present within the correct scoring period. The analyst failed to perform basic deduplication and date filtering.\r\n* Why it Matters:\r\n  Including duplicate and out-of-period records inflates the evaluation dataset size by 11.5% and distorts all performance metrics. When properly cleaned, the true holdout dataset contains exactly 5,065 unique transactions and 0 duplicates.\r\n"]
