[152.804602, "o", "* What is Wrong:\r\n  At a threshold of 0.5, the model flags 698 of 5,065 holdout transactions (13.78%). Extrapolated to our quarterly production volume of 2,800,000 transactions, this would generate 385,864 alerts per quarter, which translates to 4,287 alerts per day (assuming 90 days per quarter).\r\n  However, the Fraud Operations team has a strict daily review capacity of only 1,500 alerts per day (12 analysts, 8-hour shifts). The draft recommendation completely ignores this operational reality.\r\n* Why it Matters:\r\n  Deploying the model at threshold 0.5 would generate 4,287 daily alerts, exceeding our team's capacity by 2.85x. This would overwhelm the operations team, cause massive backlogs, lead to severe analyst burnout, and leave thousands of fraud alerts unreviewed, creating a critical security gap.\r\n\r\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\nFINDING 6: Absence of Financial Modeling and Threshold Optimization\r\n--------------------------------------------------------------------------------\r\n* Claim in Draft:\r\n  \"No further tuning is required. ... recommended for production deployment.\"\r\n* What is Wrong:\r\n  The analyst failed to conduct any cost-benefit analysis or threshold optimization using the cost parameters provided by Finance ($4,200 loss per undetected fraud, $35 cost per manual investigation).\r\n  They did not realize that threshold 0.5 is not only operationally impossible, but also financially sub-optimal.\r\n* Why it Matters:\r\n  Tuning the threshold is necessary to balance investigation costs and undetected fraud losses.\r\n  - At threshold 0.5, the projected quarterly cost is $127.27M ($13.51M investigation + $113.77M fraud loss).\r\n  - While an unconstrained cost-minimizing threshold exists at 0.29 (cost of $63.60M), it is operationally impossible as it generates 14,293 alerts/day.\r\n  - By performing a constrained optimization, we can find a threshold that satisfies the daily review capacity of 1,500 alerts while minimizing cost. This occurs at t = 0.644, generating 1,480.3 alerts/day and minimizing the quarterly cost to $192.73M ($4.66M investigation + $188.07M fraud loss).\r\n  This represents a net quarterly savings of $255.38M compared to doing nothing (baseline cost of $448.11M), while remaining fully within operational capacity.\r\n"]
